		<li id="comment-441762" class="comment even depth-2">
			<article id="div-comment-441762" class="comment-body">
				<footer class="comment-meta">
					<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/4447aa333fd2fea081fa861e83fb32cc?s=42&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/4447aa333fd2fea081fa861e83fb32cc?s=84&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-42 photo' height='42' width='42' loading='lazy' decoding='async'/>						<b class="fn">Gregory R Dressler</b> <span class="says">says:</span>					</div><!-- .comment-author -->

					<div class="comment-metadata">
						<a href="https://nexus.od.nih.gov/all/2021/03/01/nih-stands-against-structural-racism-in-biomedical-research/#comment-441762"><time datetime="2021-10-29T14:51:34-04:00">October 29, 2021 at 2:51 pm</time></a>					</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

									</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>I do not think you clearly represent the NIH grant review process.  Grants are judged on merit.  Study section members are generally not big shots in the field, rather they are mostly mid-career Professors at a variety of institutions around the country, balanced for gender and geography.  Members are selected from a pool of NIH grant awardees.   New investigators are NOT punished, quite the opposite, they get a significant bump in the percentile that gets funded.  The three assigned reviewers read the proposal carefully and must discuss and justify their scores in an oral presentation to the entire study section.  Members ask questions and challenge the views of the 3 assigned reviewers if there are any discrepancies.   I have been a permanent member on 3 different study sections and have ad-hocked others.  It is not perfect, but it is the best system we can come up with.</p>
				</div><!-- .comment-content -->

				<div class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='https://nexus.od.nih.gov/all/2021/03/01/nih-stands-against-structural-racism-in-biomedical-research/?replytocom=441762#respond' data-commentid="441762" data-postid="21420" data-belowelement="div-comment-441762" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Gregory R Dressler" aria-label='Reply to Gregory R Dressler'>Reply</a></div>			</article><!-- .comment-body -->
